Today's just not your day, man.

247
00:17:11,940 --> 00:17:13,940
Yeah. Not your week.

248
00:17:14,900 --> 00:17:16,580
You and the princess break up for one day,

249
00:17:16,610 --> 00:17:18,370
she's running off
with the freak's brother.

250
00:17:18,450 --> 00:17:19,450
<font color="#ff00ff">[chuckles]</font>

251
00:17:20,080 --> 00:17:23,410
Oh, shit. You don't know.

252
00:17:24,200 --> 00:17:27,580
Jonathan and the princess skipped
yesterday. Still haven't shown.

253
00:17:27,670 --> 00:17:30,630
But that must just be
a coincidence, right?

254
00:17:30,710 --> 00:17:31,960
<font color="#ff00ff">[laughs]</font>

255
00:17:33,840 --> 00:17:35,590
Don't take it too hard, man.

256
00:17:36,510 --> 00:17:38,840
A pretty boy like you has got
nothing to worry about.

257
00:17:39,550 --> 00:17:41,510
Plenty of bitches in the sea.

258
00:17:43,640 --> 00:17:44,980
Am I right?

259
00:17:48,770 --> 00:17:50,360
I'll be sure to leave you some.

260
00:17:57,360 --> 00:17:58,820
<font color="#ff00ff">[indistinct chatter]</font>

261
00:18:00,700 --> 00:18:01,700
<font color="#ff00ff">[sighs]</font>

262
00:18:04,620 --> 00:18:06,080
It's 15 past.

263
00:18:06,160 --> 00:18:07,710
Yeah, I know.

264
00:18:08,790 --> 00:18:10,420
Just give him time.

265
00:18:14,710 --> 00:18:16,380
That guy. There.

266
00:18:17,090 --> 00:18:20,760
- What?
- He just... just talked to himself.

267
00:18:28,730 --> 00:18:30,020
<font color="#ff00ff">[children shouting indistinctly]</font>

268
00:18:33,150 --> 00:18:36,490
<font color="#ff00ff">[child]</font> Duck, duck, duck,

269
00:18:36,570 --> 00:18:39,400
- duck, duck...
- <font color="#ff00ff">[indistinct chatter]</font>

270
00:18:46,500 --> 00:18:49,040
Duck, duck, duck...

271
00:18:54,460 --> 00:18:57,010
Duck, duck, duck...

272
00:18:59,550 --> 00:19:00,720
Duck...

273
00:19:00,800 --> 00:19:01,890
<font color="#ff00ff">[kids laugh]</font>

274
00:19:02,470 --> 00:19:05,100
Duck, duck...

275
00:19:05,180 --> 00:19:06,640
Goose!

276
00:19:06,720 --> 00:19:08,180
I think we should go.

277
00:19:30,870 --> 00:19:32,580
<font color="#ff00ff">[stalling]</font>

278
00:19:36,300 --> 00:19:37,380
<font color="#ff00ff">[gasps]</font>

279
00:19:38,010 --> 00:19:41,430
Trouble with your car, miss?
I can give you two a lift if you like.

280
00:19:43,590 --> 00:19:44,680
<font color="#ff00ff">[Nancy]</font> Jonathan.

281
00:19:53,690 --> 00:19:55,400
You sure you don't need that ride?

282
00:20:17,670 --> 00:20:18,800
Hello?

283
00:20:18,880 --> 00:20:20,340
<font color="#ff00ff">[Joyce]</font> Leave it open.

284
00:20:22,510 --> 00:20:23,800
Where the hell have you been?

285
00:20:23,880 --> 00:20:27,220
I overslept. What the hell's going on?
It's freezing.

286
00:20:31,980 --> 00:20:33,890
Hey! Knock, knock.

287
00:20:35,770 --> 00:20:37,360
We have a visitor.

288
00:20:43,200 --> 00:20:45,160
<font color="#ff00ff">[Hopper]</font> So this thing, this shadow thing.

289
00:20:45,240 --> 00:20:47,990
You told your mom it likes it like this.
It likes it cold?

290
00:20:48,990 --> 00:20:49,990
Yeah.

291
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:52,250
How do you know that?

292
00:20:53,250 --> 00:20:55,000
I just know.

293
00:20:59,710 --> 00:21:00,710
Does he talk to you?

294
00:21:01,510 --> 00:21:03,220
No. It's like...

295
00:21:03,300 --> 00:21:04,970
I don't have to think.

296
00:21:05,050 --> 00:21:06,720
I just know things now.

297
00:21:07,390 --> 00:21:09,430
Things I never did before.

298
00:21:14,770 --> 00:21:16,230
<font color="#ff00ff">[Hopper]</font> And, uh...

299
00:21:17,270 --> 00:21:18,400
what else do you know?

300
00:21:19,940 --> 00:21:21,650
<font color="#ff00ff">[Will]</font> It's hard to explain.

301
00:21:21,730 --> 00:21:25,200
It's like old memories
in the back of my head,

302
00:21:25,280 --> 00:21:28,530
only... they're not my memories.

303
00:21:29,280 --> 00:21:30,410
Okay.

304
00:21:31,870 --> 00:21:35,000
I mean, I don't think
they're old memories at all. They're...

305
00:21:36,000 --> 00:21:39,540
they're now-memories,
happening all at once, now.

306
00:21:39,630 --> 00:21:41,880
Can you describe these now-memories?

307
00:21:45,880 --> 00:21:48,470
I don't know.
It's... it's hard to explain.

308
00:21:48,550 --> 00:21:51,600
<font color="#ff00ff">[Joyce]</font> I know it's hard
but can you just... Can you try?

309
00:21:51,680 --> 00:21:53,350
For us?

310
00:21:55,680 --> 00:21:56,890
It's like...

311
00:21:57,850 --> 00:22:01,020
They're growing and spreading...

312
00:22:02,360 --> 00:22:03,360
killing.

313
00:22:03,980 --> 00:22:05,280
The memories?

314
00:22:05,990 --> 00:22:07,650
I don't know.

315
00:22:09,950 --> 00:22:10,950
Oh!

316
00:22:11,030 --> 00:22:13,870
- <font color="#ff00ff">[crying]</font> I'm sorry.
- No, no, no. It's okay, sweetie.

317
00:22:20,420 --> 00:22:22,460
Hey, hey, sweetie...

318
00:22:23,500 --> 00:22:25,710
what if you didn't have to use words?

319
00:22:38,940 --> 00:22:40,520
<font color="#ff00ff">[phone ringing]</font>

320
00:22:50,610 --> 00:22:51,700
<font color="#ff00ff">[continues ringing]</font>

321
00:22:51,780 --> 00:22:54,740
<font color="#ff00ff">[Joyce on answering machine]</font> Hey,
you've reached the Byers. We're sorry...

322
00:22:57,750 --> 00:22:58,750
<font color="#ff00ff">[Lucas]</font> Anything?

323
00:22:58,830 --> 00:23:02,500
We need to talk. AV room. Right now.

324
00:23:04,880 --> 00:23:05,880
Party members only.

325
00:23:07,050 --> 00:23:08,050
Come on, Mike.

326
00:23:08,130 --> 00:23:09,840
No! This is non-negotiable.

327
00:23:11,090 --> 00:23:12,800
- Sorry, Max.
- Sorry.

328
00:23:19,600 --> 00:23:21,350
<font color="#ff00ff">[Mike]</font> Will didn't want me to tell anyone,

329
00:23:21,440 --> 00:23:24,940
but on Halloween night
he saw a sort of shadow in the sky.

330
00:23:25,610 --> 00:23:26,860
A shadow?

331
00:23:26,940 --> 00:23:28,570
<font color="#ff00ff">[stammers]</font> What kind of shadow?

332
00:23:28,650 --> 00:23:30,400
I don't know. But it scared him.

333
00:23:31,110 --> 00:23:33,160
And if Will really has True Sight...

334
00:23:33,240 --> 00:23:35,450
I mean, if he can really see
into the Upside Down,

335
00:23:35,530 --> 00:23:37,540
maybe he saw that shadow again yesterday.

336
00:23:38,370 --> 00:23:41,080
- So that's why he was frozen like that?
- Maybe.

337
00:23:41,160 --> 00:23:42,170
Can it hurt him?

338
00:23:42,250 --> 00:23:45,000
I mean, if this shadow thing
isn't from our world...

339
00:23:45,090 --> 00:23:46,750
I'm not sure. Dustin?

340
00:23:46,840 --> 00:23:48,210
Well, if you're in another plane,

341
00:23:48,300 --> 00:23:50,130
you can't interact
with the material plane,

342
00:23:50,220 --> 00:23:52,300
so theoretically,
no, the shadow can't hurt him.

343
00:23:52,380 --> 00:23:54,010
Yeah, if that's even what's happening.

344
00:23:54,090 --> 00:23:56,680
This isn't D & D. This is real life.

345
00:23:56,760 --> 00:23:57,760
So what do we do?

346
00:23:57,850 --> 00:23:59,560
We acquire more knowledge.

347
00:23:59,640 --> 00:24:02,140
I'll go to Will's after school.
See what's going on.

348
00:24:02,230 --> 00:24:03,550
You guys stay here and find Dart.

349
00:24:03,600 --> 00:24:05,310
Dart? What's he gotta do with this?

350
00:24:05,400 --> 00:24:06,940
Will heard him in the Upside Down.

351
00:24:07,020 --> 00:24:10,440
I don't know how yet,
but he's gotta be connected to all this.

352
00:24:10,530 --> 00:24:11,610
He's gotta be.

353
00:24:12,240 --> 00:24:14,780
If we find Dart,
maybe we can solve this thing.

354
00:24:15,910 --> 00:24:17,200
Maybe we can help Will.

355
00:24:27,540 --> 00:24:28,550
<font color="#ff00ff">[sighs]</font>

356
00:24:45,440 --> 00:24:46,520
<font color="#ff00ff">[blows]</font>

357
00:25:41,580 --> 00:25:42,740
<font color="#ff00ff">[grunting]</font>

358
00:26:14,030 --> 00:26:16,700
Hey! Hey, assholes!

359
00:26:17,280 --> 00:26:18,820
Let us out of here!

360
00:26:20,450 --> 00:26:21,870
<font color="#ff00ff">[Owens]</font> Oh!

361
00:26:22,870 --> 00:26:24,830
Not very pleasant in here, is it?

362
00:26:24,910 --> 00:26:29,120
Sorry about that.
Hospitality's not our strong suit.

363
00:26:29,210 --> 00:26:31,130
You know, scientists and all.

364
00:26:34,340 --> 00:26:36,300
Yeah. Okay.

365
00:26:37,970 --> 00:26:39,340
You up for a little walk?

366
00:26:42,100 --> 00:26:44,640
- I'm assuming you're behind me.
- <font color="#ff00ff">[door opens]</font>

367
00:26:44,720 --> 00:26:48,060
"Men of science have made
abundant mistakes of every kind."

368
00:26:48,140 --> 00:26:49,640
George Sarton said that.

369
00:26:49,730 --> 00:26:52,560
You guys know who George Sarton is?
Doesn't really matter.

370
00:26:52,650 --> 00:26:55,110
The point is,
mistakes have been made. Yes.

371
00:26:55,190 --> 00:26:56,480
- Mistakes?
- Yes.

372
00:26:56,570 --> 00:26:57,690
You killed Barbara.

373
00:26:57,780 --> 00:27:01,610
Abundant mistakes, but,
the men involved with those mistakes,

374
00:27:01,700 --> 00:27:05,620
the ones responsible for what happened
to your brother and Miss Holland's death,

375
00:27:05,700 --> 00:27:08,410
they're gone.
They're gone, and for better for worse,

376
00:27:08,500 --> 00:27:10,620
I'm the schmuck they brought in
to make things better.

377
00:27:10,670 --> 00:27:13,840
But I can't make things better
without your help.

378
00:27:13,920 --> 00:27:15,550
You mean without us shutting up?

379
00:27:15,630 --> 00:27:18,920
<font color="#ff00ff">[sighs]</font> She's tough, this one.
You guys been together long?

380
00:27:19,010 --> 00:27:21,760
- We're not together.
- Wanna see what really killed your friend?

381
00:27:24,800 --> 00:27:28,220
Teddy, I brought you an audience today.
I hope you don't mind.

382
00:27:28,310 --> 00:27:29,520
<font color="#ff00ff">[Teddy]</font> More the merrier, sir.

383
00:27:33,230 --> 00:27:35,440
<font color="#ff00ff">[Owens]</font> I'd call it one hell of a mistake.

384
00:27:35,520 --> 00:27:37,030
Wouldn't you?

385
00:27:40,070 --> 00:27:45,490
See, the thing is,
we can't seem to erase our mistake...

386
00:27:45,580 --> 00:27:47,990
but we can stop it from spreading.

387
00:27:48,580 --> 00:27:51,080
Like, it's like pulling weeds.

388
00:27:51,710 --> 00:27:55,290
But imagine for a moment
if a foreign state,

389
00:27:55,380 --> 00:27:58,840
let's say, the Soviets...
If they heard about our mistake...

390
00:27:59,670 --> 00:28:02,090
do you think they would even
consider that a mistake?

391
00:28:03,590 --> 00:28:05,390
What if they tried to replicate that?

392
00:28:12,190 --> 00:28:14,770
The more attention we bring to ourselves,
the more...

393
00:28:14,850 --> 00:28:17,230
the more people like the Hollands
know the truth,

394
00:28:17,320 --> 00:28:19,530
the more likely that scenario becomes.

395
00:28:21,190 --> 00:28:24,280
You see why I have to stop
the truth from spreading, too.

396
00:28:24,360 --> 00:28:26,320
Just, same as those weeds there.

397
00:28:28,870 --> 00:28:30,750
By whatever means necessary.

398
00:28:31,790 --> 00:28:33,620
<font color="#ff00ff">[screeching]</font>

399
00:28:36,130 --> 00:28:40,000
So, we understand each other now,
don't we?

400
00:29:02,900 --> 00:29:05,450
This is more of the same.

401
00:29:05,530 --> 00:29:08,780
Oh, it's nothing. It's just scribbles.

402
00:29:09,620 --> 00:29:10,620
Wait!

403
00:29:11,870 --> 00:29:12,950
- What? What?
- Wait.

404
00:29:13,040 --> 00:29:16,370
- Wait. These black lines, see?
- <font color="#ff00ff">[Hopper]</font> What?

405
00:29:17,540 --> 00:29:19,170
Look, they connect.

406
00:29:22,300 --> 00:29:24,130
They connect.

407
00:29:24,220 --> 00:29:25,300
<font color="#ff00ff">[grunting]</font>

408
00:30:14,770 --> 00:30:16,560
Does this mean anything to you?

409
00:30:16,640 --> 00:30:17,640
No.

410
00:30:18,230 --> 00:30:21,610
<font color="#ff00ff">[sighs]</font> I mean,
is it some sort of maze or a road?

411
00:30:22,150 --> 00:30:26,900
<font color="#ff00ff">[stammers]</font> I mean, it's sort of forking
and branching like... like lightning.

412
00:30:26,990 --> 00:30:28,150
You think it's that storm?

413
00:30:28,240 --> 00:30:31,780
No, the storm he drew was
completely different. He used red.

414
00:30:31,870 --> 00:30:36,000
And this is all blue
and it has some weird dirt color.

415
00:30:37,290 --> 00:30:38,790
I mean, maybe it's roots.

416
00:30:38,870 --> 00:30:41,420
'Cause remember,
he was saying it was spreading and...

417
00:30:41,500 --> 00:30:42,880
Killing.

418
00:30:42,960 --> 00:30:44,550
He said they were killing.

419
00:30:46,760 --> 00:30:47,880
Vines.

420
00:30:54,680 --> 00:30:56,270
He's drawing vines.

421
00:30:56,350 --> 00:30:58,140
<font color="#ff00ff">[ringing]</font>

422
00:30:59,310 --> 00:31:03,230
Hey, Max. Have you seen Dustin?
We're supposed to meet after class.

423
00:31:05,110 --> 00:31:06,190
Max!

424
00:31:07,190 --> 00:31:10,700
Hey, Max! Hey, where you going?
Come on! We've gotta go look for Dart.

425
00:31:10,780 --> 00:31:12,160
Yeah, good luck with that.

426
00:31:14,990 --> 00:31:16,330
<font color="#ff00ff">[Lucas]</font> What is wrong with you?

427
00:31:16,410 --> 00:31:18,250
What is wrong with me?
What's wrong with you?

428
00:31:18,910 --> 00:31:22,330
- I don't understand.
- No! I don't understand!

429
00:31:22,420 --> 00:31:24,290
You guys act like
you want me to be your friend

430
00:31:24,380 --> 00:31:25,840
but then you treat me like garbage!

431
00:31:25,920 --> 00:31:27,630
- That's not true!
- Yes, it is!

432
00:31:27,710 --> 00:31:29,010
You go and hide in the AV Club,

433
00:31:29,090 --> 00:31:31,380
keeping secrets like we're
in second grade or something.

434
00:31:31,470 --> 00:31:33,890
You know, I thought you guys wanted me
in your party.

435
00:31:33,970 --> 00:31:36,390
- We do. But it's...
- But what?

436
00:31:37,220 --> 00:31:39,560
<font color="#ff00ff">[sighs]</font> There... there are just things.

437
00:31:39,640 --> 00:31:42,060
Things we can't tell you, all right?
For your own safety.

438
00:31:42,150 --> 00:31:43,860
- My own safety?
- Yes!

439
00:31:43,940 --> 00:31:47,280
- Because I'm a girl?
- What? No!

440
00:31:47,360 --> 00:31:49,150
Did you keep secrets from El?

441
00:31:50,900 --> 00:31:52,160
How do you know about El?

442
00:31:52,240 --> 00:31:53,570
Did you?

443
00:31:53,660 --> 00:31:55,870
That was different. Trust me. Okay?

444
00:31:55,950 --> 00:31:57,950
That was just... just different.

445
00:31:58,040 --> 00:32:00,460
Okay. You know what? Forget it, okay?

446
00:32:01,040 --> 00:32:03,460
I don't wanna be in your
stupid party anyway. I'm out.

447
00:32:04,210 --> 00:32:05,630
Have a nice life.

448
00:32:08,380 --> 00:32:10,720
- Max!
- You still stink, by the way!

449
00:32:13,340 --> 00:32:14,760
<font color="#ff00ff">[sniffs]</font> Oh, shit!

450
00:32:26,980 --> 00:32:29,690
That kid you were talking to, who is he?

451
00:32:29,780 --> 00:32:31,240
<font color="#ff00ff">[Max]</font> He's no one.

452
00:32:31,320 --> 00:32:33,360
- No one?
- This kid from my class.

453
00:32:51,840 --> 00:32:53,800
Why was he talking to you?

454
00:32:53,880 --> 00:32:55,640
It was just about
a stupid class assignment.

455
00:32:55,720 --> 00:32:58,470
- Then why're you so upset?
- I'm not!

456
00:32:58,550 --> 00:32:59,560
He causing you trouble?

457
00:33:00,260 --> 00:33:01,390
Why do you care?

458
00:33:01,470 --> 00:33:03,270
Because, Max, you're a piece of shit,

459
00:33:03,350 --> 00:33:05,770
but we're family now
whether we like it or not,

460
00:33:05,850 --> 00:33:07,690
meaning I'm stuck looking out for you.

461
00:33:08,520 --> 00:33:10,080
- What would I ever do without...
- Hey!

462
00:33:11,030 --> 00:33:12,780
This is serious shit, okay?

463
00:33:12,860 --> 00:33:14,400
I'm older than you.

464
00:33:14,490 --> 00:33:15,780
And something you learn

465
00:33:15,860 --> 00:33:19,160
is that there are a certain type of people
in this world that you stay away from,

466
00:33:19,240 --> 00:33:21,870
and that kid, Max...

467
00:33:21,950 --> 00:33:24,870
That kid is one of them.

468
00:33:26,170 --> 00:33:27,750
You stay away from him, you hear me?

469
00:33:27,830 --> 00:33:29,710
Stay away.

470
00:33:32,420 --> 00:33:33,590
<font color="#ff00ff">[engine starts]</font>

471
00:34:23,060 --> 00:34:24,350
"Ives.

472
00:34:26,020 --> 00:34:27,190
Terry."

473
00:34:45,370 --> 00:34:46,910
Jane.

474
00:35:01,930 --> 00:35:03,180
Papa.

475
00:35:29,870 --> 00:35:31,510
<font color="#ff00ff">[host on radio]</font> ...President Reagan's...

